text:
I don't like Modi or the BJP at all.  But many of the people I met in India, regardless of their religion -- Hindu, Muslim, Sikh, Catholic, Zoroastrian, etc. -- touched me greatly with not just their acceptance of others' religions, but their embracing of them, while still having their own deep spirituality.  
(One Sindhi family who had to leave Pakistan after the Partition because they were Hindu did not express bitterness at their plight, and they still welcomed me and took care of me even though I have an Islamic background.  The matriarch actually followed a lot of the Sufis from Pakistan.)  
It isn't something you see frequently in the West.  
Because of what I saw, and the history I knew, it always kind of saddened me that the Subcontinent was not united; I always looked at the violent political division at being a legacy of colonial strategy, which operated on Divide and Conquer in order to gain power.  
But under Modi/the BJP, India seems to adopting only the worse habits of the West.  
Really unfortunate.

text:
Analysis by a Bangladeshi Air Force Officer
“The Best Analysis So Far – A Must-Read That Will Uplift Your Spirits”
Complete English Translation of “The War Clouds Are Over” by Iqbal Latif

⸻

The War Clouds Are Over

By Iqbal Latif

Power, until tested, is revered. But when displayed unnecessarily, it exposes its own limits. That is the essence of deterrence: a strong leader must never swing the stick — unless certain that the blow will land precisely.

Modi had a big stick — the benefit of ambiguity, the fear of overwhelming force, and the rising global stature of India. But he used it — not for a calculated strike, but merely for a show of bravado. And in doing so, he revealed the hollowness of that power.

Now, the enemy no longer fears the stick.
Now, the world has seen that Indian airpower can be checked.
And Pakistan — the target of Modi’s strategic designs — has not emerged weakened, but awakened.
This was not just a strategic failure; it was a historic moment — when India lost its dominance not through defeat, but through overreach.

This was not a mere skirmish. It was an attempted redraw of the map of power and perception. But India’s strategy — intended to assert dominance — only ended up exposing its limitations. The Indian Air Force, long considered superior, was tested — and stopped. The stick meant to break Pakistan shattered mid-air.

Modi’s deeper plan was clear:
	1.	Provoke Pakistan into a nuclear overreaction,
	2.	Isolate it on the global stage,
	3.	Destroy its credibility.

But Pakistan didn’t blink.
It stood its ground with restraint, precision, and strategy.
Backed by Chinese ISR, radar, and missile networks, Pakistan turned potential defeat into regional balance.
	•	The myth of Rafale jets evaporated.
	•	INS Vikrant quietly withdrew.
	•	And India’s psychological dominance — its most potent weapon — was lost.

It was a trial of strength. And India showed its hand, shattering the illusion of superiority.
The Indian Air Force, once seen as invincible, has now been measured, weighed — and checked.
The entire framework of conventional superiority — built for a day like this — collapsed before the public eye.
	1.	The myth is broken.
	2.	Psychological dominance is gone.
	3.	And the dream of “Akhand Bharat” — wrapped in nationalist slogans — has washed away.

⸻

Pakistan’s Rendezvous with Destiny: From Brink to Brilliance

Last night will be remembered not for what happened — but for what didn’t:
	•	The “fall” of Islamabad,
	•	The “destruction” of Karachi Port,
	•	The “arrest” of General Asim Munir —
All were final attempts by Indian media to stage a theatrical illusion of victory — a drama of psychological conquest.

But it failed. And in that failure, a new reality emerged.

Today, as Modi looks north, he sees a restored alliance — Pakistan and China, closer than ever before.
This was Pakistan’s rendezvous with its history — an existential moment handled with dignity and precision.
The very jets India once mocked as “flying metal tubes” have redefined deterrence.

Pakistan showcased the most integrated defensive strategy and real-time coordination in modern South Asian military history.

And now, as India’s pride has been humbled, a new era begins — less of arrogance, more of humility.
The Arab world will no longer see Modi through the same lens.
Nor will Trump or the West.
Because they have seen the truth:
	1.	Pakistan stands at the crossroads of Karakoram, the Silk Road, Wagah, Khyber, and Torkham.
	2.	It holds not just geography, but the key to regional stability for 2.8 billion people.
	3.	The strategic map has shifted — and so has the world’s perspective.

⸻

Strategic Forecast: Modi’s Miscalculation and the Dawn of a New Balance

What began as a show of strength has become a textbook example of strategic error.
Modi’s goal was clear:
	1.	Assert dominance, humiliate Pakistan swiftly, and cement India’s regional supremacy.
The plan relied on Indian Air Force superiority, Rafale jets, INS Vikrant, satellite intelligence, and political swagger.
	2.	In Modi’s mind, the war was 99% won — only one final strike remained.

But the illusion shattered the moment Indian jets entered contested airspace.
Air dominance was lost not to firepower — but to something more complex: deep, real-time coordination between Pakistan and China.

Pakistan Air Force didn’t just have radars — it had eyes in space:
Chinese ISR satellites, Saab Erieye AWACS, and the PL-15 long-range air-to-air missile formed a net no Indian jet could escape.

As India moved its airpower to forward “Tiger” bases — Pakistan was watching.
PAD systems monitored silently.
And once IAF jets took off, only those who fired weapons were targeted.
Rafale pilots? According to several reports, they never even saw the missile coming.
Because with AWACS guidance, the PL-15 becomes a phantom — killing before it’s seen.

This wasn’t an air battle. It was a networked ambush.

At sea, too, the illusion fell apart.
INS Vikrant, India’s flagship carrier, was forced to retreat after radar locking by a Pakistani P-3C Orion —
A surgical humiliation, not with missiles, but with tracking and restraint.

This signaled a new deterrent reality:
India can be seen.
It can be followed.
And it can be stopped.

Modi’s dream — to “erase” Pakistan, divide it, dry its rivers, destroy its cities —
Is now just a relic of a past fantasy.

⸻

Global Impact

Pakistan, long branded a “failing state,”
has emerged as a reliable balancer.

Not an economic giant, nor a second-tier player —
But a nation that stopped the Indian Air Force,
and proved that defense isn’t about quantity — it’s about precision.

This isn’t just a strategic shift — it’s a psychological jolt.

The Islamic world, once hesitant,
now looks at Pakistan through a new lens —
For in modern warfare, respect isn’t earned through slogans, but through credible deterrence.

Indian media, which spent the night fantasizing about a “victory parade” in Islamabad,
woke up to embarrassment and silence.

From Zee News to Times Now — the dream was over.
Influencers issued apologies.
Tweets were deleted.
Senior Indian analysts began calling for accountability.

⸻

My Forecast:
	1.	Modi will retreat.
Not because he wants to — but because he has no choice.
	2.	What was imagined as a “surgical strike” has turned into a technical, political, and ideological defeat.
	3.	The India–Pakistan conflict is no longer unilateral —
It is now a regional balance of power shaped not by drama,
but by the depth of the Pakistan–China military alliance.

This was not just a blow to Modi —
It was a strategic gift to Pakistan —
Given by the very man who sought to destroy it.

He paved the way —
And now that path has become the new reality.

The curtain has lifted.
The balance has shifted.
The myth has died.

Modi — once hailed as the architect of a “New India,”
once heard with thunderous applause on global stages —
now stands in the shadow of a rising counterbalance.

Pakistan, once dismissed as a failed state —
now enjoys the tacit strategic support of China’s Western Theater Command —
a guarantee of territorial integrity in any future conflict.

The balance of power has permanently shifted.

The dream of “Akhand Bharat” is over.
The belligerent posture is gone.

It’s time the Indian public accepts the truth
that their media won’t tell them:
Pakistan is no longer the Pakistan of old —
It cannot be ignored.

Today’s PAF — dignified, precise, and confident —
is not the conduct of a failing state.
It is the face of a nation that has held the line —
and redrawn it with strength.

Let us now pursue peace —
by recognizing each other’s capabilities and dignity.
It is vital we engage with mutual respect, patience, and understanding —
not with arrogance or ignorance.

Courtesy: Zafar Islam

After gaining independence, India carried out a series of military invasions and territorial occupations:

In 1947–48, it took 16,309 sq miles of Jammu & Kashmir.

In 1948, it annexed 3,337 sq miles of Junagadh.

The same year, 82,698 sq miles of Hyderabad was taken by force.

In 1961, Goa was invaded and 1,429 sq miles absorbed.

In 1971, it split East Pakistan, seizing 57,320 sq miles.

In 1975, it annexed Sikkim, another 2,740 sq miles.

text:
To those asking why Afghans support India 🇮🇳 over Pakistan 🇵🇰 in times of conflict, let me make this clear: our issue is not with the people of Pakistan, but with the Pakistani military and political establishment which for decades has acted as an enemy to the Afghan nation, despite pretending to be a “Muslim neighbor.”

Let’s look at history and facts:
	1.	Sanctuary for destruction: After 9/11, it was Pakistan that gave military bases to the United States to launch airstrikes on Afghanistan, leading to the death of over 1 million innocent Afghans. While Afghans were burning under bombs, Pakistan was earning dollars in return.
	2.	Safe haven for terrorism: The Pakistani military openly harbored and supported the Taliban and other extremist groups who killed our teachers, our doctors, our children, and destroyed our progress. Even Osama bin Laden was found in Abbottabad, not Kabul.
	3.	Strategic depth policy: Pakistan has treated Afghanistan as its “backyard” under its evil “strategic depth” doctrine, creating instability and chaos so that Afghanistan could never stand on its feet.
	4.	Violation of Islamic brotherhood: Islam teaches us not to betray your neighbor and not to support oppressors. The Qur’an says: “Do not incline toward the oppressors, lest you be touched by the Fire…” (Surah Hud, 11:113). What Pakistan did to Afghanistan is nothing but betrayal and oppression—from supporting the Taliban to sending spies, bombs, and fake peace.
	5.	Durand Line oppression: They are still fencing the illegal Durand Line, dividing Afghan families, and killing innocent Afghans with cross-border shelling—even as we extend the hand of peace.

So yes, many Afghans support India—not because India is perfect or because we are against Muslims, but because India has never sent suicide bombers to our mosques, never funded terrorists against us, and never tried to enslave our nation through proxy war.

Until the Pakistani establishment stops treating Afghanistan as its colony and stops exporting terror in the name of Islam, the Afghan people will stand with those who respect our sovereignty, whether they are Muslim or not.

text:
Ummah unity? That’s rich.

The only consistent thing in Islamic history is that Muslim nations have spent more time fighting each other than uniting. From the Rashidun civil wars to the Ottoman-Safavid conflicts, to today’s Sunni-Shia proxy battles in Yemen and Syria — “ummah” unity has always been more theatre than theology.

Pakistan banking on “Muslim brotherhood” for financial bailouts is like a student who fails every exam and then expects his classmates to pay his tuition — because they went to the same school.

As for the Arab world, they’ve moved on. The Gulf states are now signing deals with India, investing in technology, trade, and infrastructure. Why? Because real nations invest in growth, not in exporting tired victim narratives.

And Turkey? Erdoğan’s inflation is in double digits, the lira has been sinking faster than the Titanic, and Ankara is busy cozying up to Russia and China out of desperation — not strength.

So if you’re going to invoke “ummah unity” as your economic strategy, at least update the PowerPoint — because the rest of the world sees right through the performance.

text:
@rottenfreddy3759  🔹 1. Soviet Invasion of Afghanistan (1979–1989)
Pakistan’s support was crucial for the Afghan Mujahideen — they provided training, weapons (via the CIA), and safe havens.

➡ Without Pakistan's help:

The Mujahideen might have failed to resist the USSR effectively.

The Soviet Union could have remained in Afghanistan longer or even succeeded in creating a puppet regime.

The Cold War might’ve tilted in favor of the Soviets in South Asia.

🔹 2. Refugee Crisis
Over 5 million Afghan refugees crossed into Pakistan since 1979.

➡ Without Pakistani shelter:

Iran and Central Asia would have faced enormous pressure.

Humanitarian crises would’ve worsened.

The Pashtun population distribution would have been drastically different.


🔹 3. Regional Power Balance
Pakistan’s involvement shaped not just Afghan history, but India-Pakistan dynamics too.

➡ Without involvement:

India might have had more influence in Afghanistan.

Pakistan might have focused more on its internal development or other strategic fronts.

text: Bangladesh has valid, historically documented reasons to remain wary of forging close ties with Pakistan, stemming from the systematic genocide committed by the Pakistani military during the 1971 Liberation War. According to declassified documents, international journalists, and the Hamoodur Rahman Commission Report, the Pakistani Army and its collaborators were responsible for the mass killing of an estimated 300,000 to 3 million people, including students, intellectuals, scientists, and civilians, and the violation of approximately 200,000 to 400,000 women, as reported by the UN and the Bangladeshi government. Targeted massacres took place in places like Dhaka University, where intellectuals and students were brutally executed. On March 25, 1971, during "Operation Searchlight," the Pakistani military initiated a campaign to silence Bengali demands for autonomy by launching one of the most violent crackdowns in South Asian history. Entire villages were burned, women were taken to camps and subjected to inhumane abuse, and newborns were murdered in front of their families. These acts were not collateral damage of war, they were calculated. The Pakistani state explicitly denied Bengali identity, suppressed the Bengali language, and sought to maintain dominance by terrorizing the population into submission. The victims were predominantly Muslim, revealing that religious identity was no shield against ethnic and linguistic persecution. To this day, Pakistan has not officially apologized for the atrocities of 1971. Many war criminals were protected or later integrated into Pakistani politics. There is a persistent lack of remorse, justice, or reconciliation from the Pakistani state, which Bangladeshis view as a refusal to acknowledge the blood on its hands. Therefore, any political or social attempt to normalize relations with Pakistan without accountability undermines the memory of the victims, the sacrifices of the Mukti Bahini, and the very foundation of Bangladeshi independence. Friendship cannot be built on denial, silence, or historical amnesia. It must be earned through truth, justice, and repentance, none of which Pakistan has offered.

text:
@Argus_The_DarkAngel  That’s a sweet sentiment—but let’s come back down to Earth for a moment.

If by “revelation” you mean a handful of emotional online posts, that’s not a diplomatic shift—it’s a Twitter mood swing. Bangladesh–Pakistan relations are still diplomatically cold, and no amount of wishful slogans changes that. Bangladesh hasn’t forgotten the 1971 genocide, when over 3 million Bangladeshis were killed and thousands of women raped by the Pakistani military. To this day, Pakistan has never officially apologized, and Bangladeshis still commemorate the Liberation War every year with pride and pain. That history is not erased by a few online “brother” comments.

Economically, diplomatically, and strategically, Bangladesh is closely aligned with India, and that hasn’t changed. You can’t wish away deep economic integration, joint border coordination, and regional security partnerships with a paragraph of sentiment. There’s no “uprising.” There’s no strategic pivot. There’s no evidence of Bangladesh cutting ties with India, rejecting trade, or signing security agreements with Pakistan. That’s not how statecraft works.

You say “India can’t control anything about Bangladesh”—but nobody said it does. Bangladesh is a sovereign nation. But sovereignty doesn’t mean aligning yourself with a collapsing state apparatus like Pakistan’s, which is lurching from one economic crisis to another, and where even basic governance is under strain. Aligning with Pakistan “without hesitation” isn’t loyalty—it’s strategic blindness.

Brotherhood is beautiful when it’s grounded in reality. But slogans don’t feed people, secure borders, or build futures. Bangladesh’s prosperity has come from independence, economic growth, regional stability, and smart diplomacy—not emotional alliances with militaries who once turned Dhaka into a graveyard.

So yes, may you have a great day too—but preferably with your eyes open.

text:
@adawg9533  To those asking why Afghans support India over Pakistan in times of conflict, let me make this clear: our issue is not with the people of Pakistan, but with the Pakistani military and political establishment—which for decades has acted as an enemy to the Afghan nation, despite pretending to be a “Muslim neighbor.”

Let’s look at history and facts:
	1.	Sanctuary for destruction: After 9/11, it was Pakistan that gave military bases to the United States to launch airstrikes on Afghanistan, leading to the death of over 1 million innocent Afghans. While Afghans were burning under bombs, Pakistan was earning dollars in return.
	2.	Safe haven for terrorism: The Pakistani military openly harbored and supported the Taliban and other extremist groups who killed our teachers, our doctors, our children, and destroyed our progress. Even Osama bin Laden was found in Abbottabad, not Kabul.
	3.	Strategic depth policy: Pakistan has treated Afghanistan as its “backyard” under its evil “strategic depth” doctrine, creating instability and chaos so that Afghanistan could never stand on its feet.
	4.	Violation of Islamic brotherhood: Islam teaches us not to betray your neighbor and not to support oppressors. The Qur’an says: “Do not incline toward the oppressors, lest you be touched by the Fire…” (Surah Hud, 11:113). What Pakistan did to Afghanistan is nothing but betrayal and oppression—from supporting the Taliban to sending spies, bombs, and fake peace.
	5.	Durand Line oppression: They are still fencing the illegal Durand Line, dividing Afghan families, and killing innocent Afghans with cross-border shelling—even as we extend the hand of peace.

So yes, many Afghans support India—not because India is perfect or because we are against Muslims, but because India has never sent suicide bombers to our mosques, never funded terrorists against us, and never tried to enslave our nation through proxy war.

Until the Pakistani establishment stops treating Afghanistan as its colony and stops exporting terror in the name of Islam, the Afghan people will stand with those who respect our sovereignty, whether they are Muslim or not.

It’s about how you handle pressure, how you represent your country, and whether your decisions actually make sense in the bigger picture. He hasn’t exactly proven himself in that department.

text:
The idea of a “Greater Israel” — meaning Israel expanding to control all territory from the Nile to the Euphrates — is not the official policy of the State of Israel, nor is it supported by most Israelis or the Israeli government.

Here’s a breakdown:

1. The “Greater Israel” Myth:
	•	Antisemites and anti-Zionists often claim that Israel seeks to conquer large parts of the Middle East, citing a misinterpretation of biblical texts or extremist fringe views.
	•	In reality, the vast majority of Israeli Jews, including mainstream politicians, do not support such an idea.
	•	The Israeli Declaration of Independence supports peaceful coexistence and never mentions “expanding borders.”

2. Who does support it?
	•	Only fringe ideological groups (like some religious extremists or Kahanist-type figures) dream of “Greater Israel.”
	•	These groups have no real power in Israeli politics, and their views are rejected by most Israeli Jews, including secular, religious-Zionist, and centrist communities.

3. Reality:
	•	Israel has actually given up land for peace (like Sinai to Egypt, Gaza disengagement in 2005).
	•	Its real strategic interest is security, not imperial expansion.
	•	Even Netanyahu and Likud, considered right-wing, have never made “Greater Israel” an official platform.

4. Why this lie is pushed:
	•	To demonize Israel and compare it to colonial empires.
	•	It feeds pan-Arabist and Islamist narratives that paint Israel as a regional aggressor rather than a state defending its existence.

So no — Israel does not seek a “Greater Israel”, and saying so is propaganda, not fact.

text:
3:45 ,The word "Bharat" comes from ancient times — long before the names "India" or any colonial term existed. It is named after King Bharata, a mighty emperor mentioned in the Mahabharata and ancient Hindu texts like the Puranas.

He was a legendary ruler who united many lands under Dharma, strength, and knowledge. Because of his legacy, the land came to be known as “Bharatvarsha” — the realm of Bharata.

This name is not just a label — it's a symbol of civilizational pride. It reflects our own identity, rooted in Sanatan dharma, culture, and history. Even our Constitution begins with:
“India, that is Bharat…”

So Bharat is not just a name — it’s who we are. A nation born from its own soil, not from foreign definitions.
author: @INGOBRO

text:
2:03, Akhand Bharat is not just an idea — it's a historical truth and a rightful demand.
The regions now called Pakistan, Bangladesh, Afghanistan, Nepal, Sri Lanka, and even the Maldives were once part of ancient Bharat, united under powerful Hindu empires and bound by the same civilization, language roots, and culture.

Over centuries, this land was invaded, divided, and stolen — first by foreign Islamic invaders, then by British colonizers, and finally broken through the forced Partition of 1947, which tore our civilization apart. Indians never chose this division — it was imposed.

That’s why the call for Akhand Bharat is not about aggression — it’s about reclaiming what was ours, what was taken from us through bloodshed, deceit, and foreign politics. It’s a demand born from memory, pain, and truth. Our land wasn’t divided naturally — it was broken.

Akhand Bharat lives in our hearts because our civilization was one — and no amount of false borders can erase that.
author: @INGOBRO

text:
1:40 , He Said India Occupied Kasmir, 
Who occupied Kashmir first?

In 1947, after India and Pakistan became independent, the ruler of Kashmir (a Hindu king of a Muslim-majority state) wanted to stay independent.

But Pakistan sent tribal fighters to invade Kashmir on October 22, 1947. This was the first act of occupation.

In response, the Maharaja asked India for help and legally joined India by signing the Instrument of Accession on October 26, 1947. Indian troops then pushed back the invaders.

So, Pakistan occupied parts of Kashmir first, and India entered only after a legal request by the ruler.

text:
It's misleading to present a few tweets from Indian users as the voice of an entire nation. Incidents like the 26/11 attacks, the Kargil War, the Parliament attack, and the Uri strike—where countless innocent lives were lost, including Muslims—are stark reminders of the terrorism India has endured. Most of these attacks were carried out by Pakistan-based terrorist groups, yet India consistently chose diplomatic responses for years.

However, when diplomacy failed to stop the bloodshed, targeted counter-terrorism operations were necessary and justified. These were not random acts of aggression but precise strikes on known terror camps.

If fairness is the goal, then why ignore what the Pakistani military did to fellow Muslims in Bangladesh in 1971? Or the ongoing human rights violations against the Baloch people? India, home to more Muslims than Pakistan, remains a diverse and democratic society where Muslims hold key political and social roles. Even prominent leaders like Asaduddin Owaisi have openly condemned Pakistan’s actions.

Selective outrage and narratives driven by diaspora biases do a disservice to the truth and to the principles of balanced journalism.

text:
Just who is this blind deaf condemned servant in Isaiah 42:18-20? Christians and Muslims both agree that Isaiah makes it clear that the servant of condemnation is none other than the nation of Israel: Who is blind like the one in covenant with me, blind like the servant of the Lord? [Isaiah 42:19]

“one in covenant with me” is a clear reference to the nation of Israel who were in covenant with God at the time Isaiah made this prophecy. Isaiah goes on to make it even more explicit: Who handed Jacob over to become loot, and Israel to the plunderers? [Isaiah 42:24]


Numbers 23:19 "GOD is not a human male—he doesn't lie, nor is he a human being—he never vacillates. Once he speaks up, he's going to act, isn't he? Once he makes a promise, he'll fulfill it, won't he?

📖 Isaiah 42:21 "The LORD is well pleased for his righteousness' sake; he will magnify the law and make it honorable." Question: How did the Jewish and Christians's God magnify Law to make people righteous ⁉️



Isaiah 42: (1-17) describe a momentous servant (Prophet Muhammad ﷺ) in extremely positive terms, one who will be a “light for the Gentiles”(see 42:6), will rise from Madina (see 42:11) to free people from darkness of idols worships by fighting against injustice (polythesim) to guide the blind (42:16) to establish justice on earth 🌎 (see 42:4) with a new law (see 42:21).


Because 'The nation of Israel' is condemned as blind deaf in Isaiah 42:19,24 for rejecting Prophet Muhammad (ﷺ), the guiding servant in Isaiah 42:1-17 The victory of the Muslims was foretold in Bible.


Why does Isaiah (42:11) speaks about the rejoicing of the inhabitants of Ishmael's son Kedar who lived in Medina ⁉️To identify the Prophet of the Jews ⁉️ "A light for the Gentiles (Non-Jews)”(42:6).


Yes, Isaiah 60:7 talks about the Islamic sacrifices by the sons of Ishmael (peace be upon him). And the rising of the Final prophet Muhammad (ﷺ) of Bible (Read Isaiah 42:1-13) from Medina (See 42:11).



Because the Arabia shall Rejoice by His coming. Moving to Isaiah 42:11, we see that prophecy gives 2 special places; Kedar and Sela: 📖 Isaiah 42:11 Let the wilderness and the cities thereof lift up their voice, the villages that Kedar doth inhabit; let the inhabitants of Sela sing, let them shout from the top of the mountains.

The Old Testament scholar Charles Foster also identifies the the "Land of Kedar" with ‘Hedjaz’ which is Western Saudi Arabia including its famous cities of Makkah and Madina. [Charles Foster, The historical geography of Arabia, P. 130]

Yes, 📖 Isaiah 42:11 prophecies that this Arabian Messenger will migrate to Medina (Biblical Midian where Prophet Moses also migrated...) And people of Sela in Medina will sing for joy to welcome the true Prophet Muhammad (ﷺ) of the Bible.

Yes, Isaiah 42:11 hints that This righteous Prophet Muhammad (ﷺ) will rise from the  Land of Ishmael's son Ke'dar who used to lived in Medina to eliminate falsehood and spread justice ⚖️ throughout the world 🌍.


Yes, Isaiah 42 Verse 11 connects that awaited one with the descendants of Kedar. Who is Kedar? According to Genesis 25:13, Kedar was the second son of Ishmael, the grandfather of the Arab nation, the ancestor of the Prophet Muhammad (ﷺ).

One of the earliest biographies of the Prophet Muhammad (ﷺ), Tabaqat Ibn Sa’d (d. 845 CE), documents one of the chains of genealogy, which confirms that the Prophet was a direct descendant of Ishmael through his second son Kedar. 

Hayden’s Bible dictionary states: Mohammad is said to have been of the Bene-Kedar [sons of Kedar] [A Bible Dictionary, Hayden Series, edited by Rev. Charles Boutell, p. 386].


The righteous mission of establishing justice on earth will require special help from GOD, which is conveyed by the figurative words “And will hold Your hand”. Once “GOD holds the hand of anyone”, it is impossible to defeat that person. GOD uses that person as an instrument to wipe out evil and manifest His judgement on evil doers. 


📖 Isaiah 42:4- He will not falter or be discouraged till he establishes justice on earth. In his teaching the islands will put their hope.



Notice that 📖 Isaiah 42:4 states that the islands will put their hope in his law, implying he will bring forth something new, something different, as the Law of Moses already existed at the time Isaiah made this prophecy. Another point is that the islands aresaid to put their hope in his new Torah in the future tense, again implying it is a new law and therefore can’t be a reference to the Torah of Moses which already existed at the time that Isaiah made this prophecy.

Yes, 📖 Isaiah 42:21 also stated that the God of Bible would magnify the Law to make people righteous. It hints about Al-Quran, Shariah Law.

One who will be a “light for the Gentiles (non-jews/non-christians)” (📖 Isaiah 42:6), will “open eyes that are blind” and “free people from darkness” (📖 Isaiah 42:7) of idols worships.


📖 Isaiah 42:8- I am the Lord; that is my name! I will not yield my glory to another or my praise to idols. 


📖 Isaiah 42:9 See, the former things have taken place, and new things (Al-Quran, Shariah law) I (God) declare; before they spring into being I announce them to you.

“Paraclete” (Ahmad/Praised one) that Easa Messiah foretold to come after him was described as one who “shall not speak of himself, but whatsoever he shall hear (from God through angel), that shall he speak . . .(John 16:13)

📖 Isaiah 42:10- "Sing to the Lord a new song, his praise from the ends of the earth, you who go down to the sea, and all that is in it, you islands, and all who live in them." 

Isaiah informs us that this special person will bring something new. The statement “a new song” means a new way of worship. This is exactly what Islam represents. The emphasis on the new song here is singing the praise of GOD all over the earth. The Qur’an opens with the statement “Praise be to GOD, LORD of the worlds” and is recited by Muslims all over the world during prayers every day.


📖 Isaiah 42:12- Let them give glory to the Lord and proclaim his praise in the islands. This seems to indicate that this special person’s impact will be far reaching.

Islam spread rapidly throughout the Arabian peninsula, even reaching as far as Spain in just over a hundred years after Prophet Muhammad (ﷺ).

The law of Islam spread as far east as northern China and as far west as southern France. In fact many isles did wait for his law and when the Islamic law came to them with the Muslim armies, they welcomed their liberators. This happened in Syria, Egypt and Spain. With the advent of Islam all the oppressive powers surrounding Arabia fell one after another and the masses could live in peace from then on. In the Qur’an GOD commanded the Muslims to go on a rescue mission.

Allaah’s Messenger (ﷺ) wrote letters to the kings of the different lands, calling them to Islaam; so this shows that he was a Messenger sent to the whole of the people of the earth.  And he was commanded with fighting jihaad until the people entered into Islaam; so this shows that his Messengership `alayhis–salaatu was-salaam was universal.



📖 42:13- The Lord will march out like a champion, like a warrior and will triumph over his enemies. Let us see how the Qur’an confirms this in the battle of Badr when around 300 ill-armed Muslims faced a thousand strong army of the pagans to wipe out evil and manifest His judgment on evil doers. 📖 Al-Quran ch 8 verses 17-19 


📖 I will lead the blind by ways they have not known, along unfamiliar paths I will guide them; I will turn the darkness into light before them and make the rough places smooth. These are the things I will do; I will not forsake them. But those who trust in idols, who say to images, ‘You are our gods,’ will be turned back in utter shame. [Isaiah 42:16-17]


Throughout 📖 Isaiah 42 there is the theme of idolatry, describing those who worship idols as “blind” and being in “darkness”. It is also said that the idolaters will be “turned back in utter shame (📖 Isaiah 42:17)


This  is unlikely to be a reference to Jesus Christ because, unlike the final Prophet Muhammad (ﷺ) whose lifetime opponents were primarily idol worshippers, Jesus’ opponents during his ministry were the Jewish religious leaders, the Sadducees and Pharisees.

His people, the Israelites, were monotheists and not idol worshippers. On one occasion Jesus Christ even told his disciples to stay away from the idol worshipping Gentiles, the exact opposite of what Isaiah prophesied. The Gospel of Matthew tells us that: 📖 These twelve Jesus sent out with the following instructions: ‘Do not go among the Gentiles…[Matthew 10:5]


While 📖 Isaiah 42: 6 clearly said that The God of Bible would make this righteous servant Prophet Muhammad (ﷺ) a Light for the gentiles and a covenant for the people to bring justice to the Nations (Isaiah 42:1) with the new Shariah law (Isaiah 42:4, 42:21) prescribed by the God of Bible

text:
To those asking why Afghans support India 🇮🇳 over Pakistan 🇵🇰 in times of conflict, let me make this clear: our issue is not with the people of Pakistan, but with the Pakistani military and political establishment which for decades has acted as an enemy to the Afghan nation, despite pretending to be a “Muslim neighbor.”

Let’s look at history and facts:
	1.	Sanctuary for destruction: After 9/11, it was Pakistan that gave military bases to the United States to launch airstrikes on Afghanistan, leading to the death of over 1 million innocent Afghans. While Afghans were burning under bombs, Pakistan was earning dollars in return.
	2.	Safe haven for terrorism: The Pakistani military openly harbored and supported the Taliban and other extremist groups who killed our teachers, our doctors, our children, and destroyed our progress. Even Osama bin Laden was found in Abbottabad, not Kabul.
	3.	Strategic depth policy: Pakistan has treated Afghanistan as its “backyard” under its evil “strategic depth” doctrine, creating instability and chaos so that Afghanistan could never stand on its feet.
	4.	Violation of Islamic brotherhood: Islam teaches us not to betray your neighbor and not to support oppressors. The Qur’an says: “Do not incline toward the oppressors, lest you be touched by the Fire…” (Surah Hud, 11:113). What Pakistan did to Afghanistan is nothing but betrayal and oppression—from supporting the Taliban to sending spies, bombs, and fake peace.
	5.	Durand Line oppression: They are still fencing the illegal Durand Line, dividing Afghan families, and killing innocent Afghans with cross-border shelling—even as we extend the hand of peace.

So yes, many Afghans support India—not because India is perfect or because we are against Muslims, but because India has never sent suicide bombers to our mosques, never funded terrorists against us, and never tried to enslave our nation through proxy war.

Until the Pakistani establishment stops treating Afghanistan as its colony and stops exporting terror in the name of Islam, the Afghan people will stand with those who respect our sovereignty, whether they are Muslim or not.

text:
As an Afghan, it's important to understand why some Afghans choose to support India — not necessarily out of loyalty or admiration, but because of the long and troubled history with Pakistan. For decades, Pakistan has maintained a hostile stance toward Afghanistan, from political interference to carrying out airstrikes on Afghan soil. Given that history, it's understandable that some Afghans would align themselves with countries that oppose Pakistan. It’s not always about supporting India itself — sometimes, it’s simply about standing against a country that has caused harm to ours.

However, many people overlook the reality of India’s rising nationalism and how it affects its own Muslim population. The treatment of Muslims in India under its current political leadership is deeply concerning and shouldn’t be ignored or excused.

Personally, I believe in standing with our fellow Muslim neighbors and promoting unity rather than division. That said, supporting our neighbors doesn't mean blindly backing governments — especially not the Pakistani government, which has its own issues and history of harming Afghanistan. There's a clear difference between supporting people and supporting regimes.

text:
The ideas of Akhand Bharat and the Greater Israel project are both expansionist-nationalist visions rooted in historical, religious, and cultural claims. While these concepts are not official state policies (and are often denied by governments), they are promoted by ideological groups tied to Hindutva in India and Zionism in Israel, especially in their far-right expressions.

Here’s a breakdown of the similarities between Akhand Bharat and Greater Israel:

1. Ideological Roots in Religious Nationalism

Akhand Bharat is a Hindutva vision of a united “undivided India” that includes modern-day India, Pakistan, Bangladesh, Nepal, Bhutan, Afghanistan, Sri Lanka, and Tibet.

Greater Israel is a vision drawn from biblical and religious Zionism, claiming land from the Nile to the Euphrates, which could include parts of Lebanon, Syria, Jordan, Iraq, Egypt, and the Palestinian territories.

Similarity: Both envision a revival of a mythologized ancient or religious homeland, to restore national or religious glory.

2. Revisionist Historical Narratives

Akhand Bharat claims that the Indian subcontinent was once a unified Hindu civilization before foreign (especially Muslim and British) invasions.

Greater Israel draws on biblical claims of the land promised to the Israelites by God.

Similarity: Both rely on mythological or ancient historical narratives to legitimize modern political ideologies.

3. Ethnic and Religious Exclusivism

Hindutva envisions India as a Hindu-first nation, with other religions tolerated only if they accept Hindu cultural dominance.

Zionism, especially in its extreme forms, sees Israel as a Jewish homeland, with increasing calls to exclude or subjugate Palestinians.

Similarity: Both ideologies, at their extremes, support ethnoreligious homogeneity and view minorities as demographic or ideological threats.

4. Justification of Settlements and Occupation

Zionists have built Jewish settlements in the West Bank, considered illegal under international law, to “reclaim” ancestral lands.

Hindutva groups support demographic and legal changes in Kashmir (post-Article 370) and the Northeast to “integrate” them into Hindu India.

Similarity: Strategic settlement and demographic engineering to change the character of contested or minority regions.

5. Role of Militant Ideologies

Akhand Bharat is promoted by the RSS and Sangh Parivar, which operate grassroots and paramilitary networks.

Greater Israel has been pushed by settler movements, Kahanist factions, and right-wing Zionist parties.

Similarity: Both are driven by ideologically hardline, often violent groups operating outside formal politics, but with close ties to ruling parties.

6. Political Denial vs. Ideological Reality

Indian leaders often distance themselves from Akhand Bharat publicly, but imagery (like murals in Parliament) and rhetoric suggest otherwise.

Israeli governments officially reject Greater Israel, but settlement expansion and annexation policies align with it in practice.

Similarity: Both concepts are denied diplomatically but promoted ideologically, often through education, propaganda, or symbolism.

7. Perception of Civilizational Conflict

Akhand Bharat portrays Hindus as under siege from centuries of Muslim and colonial rule.

Greater Israel frames Jewish survival as dependent on dominance in a hostile Arab world.

Similarity: Both see themselves as civilizations under existential threat, justifying territorial expansion as self-defense or revival.

8. Diaspora Support

Hindu nationalist groups in the U.S., U.K., and Canada fund and promote the Akhand Bharat idea.

Pro-Zionist lobbies and Christian evangelicals support Greater Israel in the U.S. and Europe.

Similarity: Both visions receive significant ideological and financial backing from diasporas.

Conclusion

Akhand Bharat and the Greater Israel project are two ideological visions rooted in religious nationalism, territorial expansion, and historical revisionism. While not formal state policies, they deeply influence domestic politics, foreign policy postures, and attitudes toward minorities.

They represent a broader global trend of ethno-nationalist expansionism, which challenges secularism, pluralism, and international norms — with real consequences for peace and stability in their respective regions.
